WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.860
 - Hello, and welcome to another walk-through for Django

00:00:03.860 --> 00:00:05.260
 for everybody.

00:00:05.260 --> 00:00:08.780
 This is kind of a supplement to tutorial two.

00:00:08.780 --> 00:00:11.360
 In tutorial two, you're playing with models.py,

00:00:11.360 --> 00:00:13.420
 and if you go through the tutorial,

00:00:13.420 --> 00:00:16.580
 they'll have you do a thing, and then they'll do another thing,

00:00:16.580 --> 00:00:18.260
 and they're kind of showing you migrations

00:00:18.260 --> 00:00:21.980
 and how the migrations happen.

00:00:21.980 --> 00:00:26.260
 And if you get 'em to have a mistake,

00:00:26.260 --> 00:00:30.260
 you know, if you make a mistake, then you

00:00:30.260 --> 00:00:32.780
 can get to the point where you need help or whatever,

00:00:32.780 --> 00:00:36.260
 and sometimes it's easier to just wipe out your database.

00:00:36.260 --> 00:00:39.300
 But if you've added a question or added some choices

00:00:39.300 --> 00:00:41.940
 or built models, you've got to do all that stuff.

00:00:41.940 --> 00:00:46.060
 But it's sometimes just easier to redo some of those things.

00:00:46.060 --> 00:00:50.540
 So I'm going to show you what to do if your model/database gets

00:00:50.540 --> 00:00:51.100
 messed up.

00:00:51.100 --> 00:00:53.900
 And like your manage.py make migrations and migrate

00:00:53.900 --> 00:00:57.020
 are not doing what you think, or they're giving you weird errors.

00:00:57.020 --> 00:00:59.100
 Now, if they're getting a syntax error,

00:00:59.100 --> 00:01:01.780
 make sure you do a Python manage.py check, right,

00:01:01.780 --> 00:01:05.420
 before you declare that your database is messed up.

00:01:05.420 --> 00:01:14.300
 So let me go into my site.

00:01:14.300 --> 00:01:15.340
 So here I am now.

00:01:15.340 --> 00:01:16.260
 Here's all my files.

00:01:20.700 --> 00:01:25.140
 So here I should do it, but before I declare that the database

00:01:25.140 --> 00:01:28.300
 is a problem, manage.py check.

00:01:28.300 --> 00:01:35.660
 Oh, I messed that up.

00:01:35.660 --> 00:01:44.380
 I'm in my virtual environment, of course.

00:01:44.380 --> 00:01:46.580
 OK, so we got no issues now.

00:01:46.580 --> 00:01:48.540
 So that's good.

00:01:48.540 --> 00:01:50.820
 So I've got a couple of commands here.

00:01:50.820 --> 00:01:51.660
 Let me explain this.

00:01:51.660 --> 00:01:54.140
 Before I'm going to actually delete these,

00:01:54.140 --> 00:01:56.500
 I want to show you where the migration--

00:01:56.500 --> 00:01:59.780
 I'll probably show you this.

00:01:59.780 --> 00:02:03.340
 So I have a thing called polls2, and I got all the polls running.

00:02:03.340 --> 00:02:05.700
 So this is like in tutorial 2.

00:02:05.700 --> 00:02:10.500
 The migrations are in files with a number,

00:02:10.500 --> 00:02:11.500
 and they're Python files.

00:02:11.500 --> 00:02:15.420
 So if you recall, migrations are portable representations

00:02:15.420 --> 00:02:17.620
 of what happens in the database.

00:02:17.620 --> 00:02:24.380
 And then the migrate creates the file db.sqlite.

00:02:24.380 --> 00:02:27.620
 So if you want to really start over,

00:02:27.620 --> 00:02:31.940
 you've got to get rid of both the migrations and the db.sqlite

00:02:31.940 --> 00:02:36.580
 file, and then you can start completely fresh.

00:02:36.580 --> 00:02:38.340
 I mean, you can sort of do parts of them,

00:02:38.340 --> 00:02:41.460
 but I'm like, if you're messed up here in tutorial 2,

00:02:41.460 --> 00:02:43.660
 it's probably easier to just get rid of them both.

00:02:43.660 --> 00:02:47.340
 So at this point, my application is going to stop working.

00:02:47.340 --> 00:02:51.460
 So I get rid of the migrations, and then I

00:02:51.460 --> 00:02:54.300
 get rid of my database.

00:02:54.300 --> 00:02:56.060
 And so at this point, the only thing

00:02:56.060 --> 00:02:58.220
 I've got that has to do with anything

00:02:58.220 --> 00:03:03.900
 that has to do with my database is a few models.py files.

00:03:03.900 --> 00:03:07.140
 And this is where we are editing our code,

00:03:07.140 --> 00:03:09.380
 and so this polls to models.py.

00:03:09.380 --> 00:03:11.820
 And my particular example is the code

00:03:11.820 --> 00:03:14.900
 that's going to be effective, because just because I've

00:03:14.900 --> 00:03:17.260
 got all the versions running at the same time,

00:03:17.260 --> 00:03:19.300
 that's why you're seeing this.

00:03:19.300 --> 00:03:25.180
 So the next thing you do is python3 or python manage.py

00:03:25.180 --> 00:03:28.100
 make migrations.

00:03:28.100 --> 00:03:29.780
 So what make migrations is doing is

00:03:29.780 --> 00:03:32.740
 it's reading all these models.py files,

00:03:32.740 --> 00:03:34.980
 and it's writing this file.

00:03:34.980 --> 00:03:38.220
 So I got rid of that file, but now if I do an ls,

00:03:38.220 --> 00:03:40.180
 you'll see that it's come back.

00:03:40.180 --> 00:03:42.740
 And sometimes you might see an 002, et cetera,

00:03:42.740 --> 00:03:45.140
 and then you throw it away, and you make it fresh,

00:03:45.140 --> 00:03:47.060
 and you should only see an 001.

00:03:47.060 --> 00:03:53.100
 And then you can say python manage py migrate.

00:03:53.100 --> 00:03:58.300
 And then that, well, if you'll do an ls--

00:03:58.300 --> 00:03:59.260
 let me Control-C there.

00:03:59.260 --> 00:04:01.780
 If I do an ls, you'll see that there--

00:04:01.780 --> 00:04:02.580
 wait a second.

00:04:02.580 --> 00:04:07.620
 How come that-- no, the dbsqlite3 is zero size.

00:04:07.620 --> 00:04:12.780
 So I'm going to do python3 or python manage--

00:04:12.780 --> 00:04:18.700
 sorry, my mac migrate.

00:04:18.700 --> 00:04:23.300
 So that's reading these files, plus a whole bunch

00:04:23.300 --> 00:04:25.540
 of other ones, and actually creating databases.

00:04:25.540 --> 00:04:30.820
 So now if I say ls minus l, my dbsqlite3 is back,

00:04:30.820 --> 00:04:33.380
 and I might have to create a super user.

00:04:33.380 --> 00:04:35.740
 If I created a super user account,

00:04:35.740 --> 00:04:38.460
 then I'm going to have to create one again.

00:04:38.460 --> 00:04:40.100
 And so I'm going to do that.

00:04:42.780 --> 00:04:47.780
 j4e choc.

00:04:47.780 --> 00:04:49.260
 Csave@umrsh.edu.

00:05:12.500 --> 00:05:14.580
 I should make my passwords easier to type.

00:05:14.580 --> 00:05:17.340
 Now at this point, things should start working.

00:05:17.340 --> 00:05:21.340
 But again, if I created any data,

00:05:21.340 --> 00:05:23.380
 like a question or something, it was gone.

00:05:23.380 --> 00:05:24.580
 It was gone at that moment.

00:05:24.580 --> 00:05:27.500
 When I got rid of that database, dbsqlite3,

00:05:27.500 --> 00:05:28.780
 it is literally gone.

00:05:28.780 --> 00:05:33.940
 So it's gone now, and away we go.

00:05:33.940 --> 00:05:36.180
 And again, this is just if you can't

00:05:36.180 --> 00:05:38.820
 seem to make these migrations or migrates work,

00:05:38.820 --> 00:05:41.860
 back up, start over, and then reduce some of the work.

00:05:41.860 --> 00:05:45.740
 And that probably will be a good way to get things done.

00:05:45.740 --> 00:05:47.280
 Cheers.

